You can create private chutes which can only be called by your user. We don't have organizational accounts currently, but you could create multiple api keys under one account, each with only access to call one (or more) of your private chutes. So you can limit access to select authorizations, just not quite "share model with other users" just yet.

The main caveat for your use case right now is the ability  (necessity really) for miners to download the model weights and view the code. Chutes (in it's current state until we have TEE) is run on a decentralized, permissionless network of miners that are able to view the code/model weights (they need to download the docker images and run them).  If you don't want the model weights public on HF, you can actually build a "chute" with the model weights pre-downloaded so it never exposes an HF key etc.

When we have TEE, the entire system will be encrypted and really invisible and inaccessible (we can limit via RBAC blanket bans of various access mechanisms, code can only be retrieved after attestation, etc.), but until then theoretically one of the miners can view your code and the model weights.

So yes, you can run a private model and/or source code, but that is technically visible by miners and therefore not guaranteed to be 100% secure.

It's a slightly annoying process right now to use the CLI if you originally registered on the website and did not provide a hotkey/coldkey.

First, you need to create a new coldkey and hotkey with the bittensor CLI.
```
btcli wallet new_coldkey --n_words 24 --wallet.name your-username
btcli wallet new_hotkey --wallet.name your-username --n_words 24 --wallet.hotkey your-hotkey
```

Then, you need to create a file, `~/.chutes/config.ini` meant to be somewhat like an AWS config file.
The template for that file is this:
```
[api]
base_url = https://api.chutes.ai

[auth]
username = me
user_id = uid
hotkey_seed = replaceme
hotkey_name = replaceme
hotkey_ss58address = replaceme

[payment]
address = replaceme
developer_payment_address = replaceme
```

You can get most of the user details from the `/users/me` endpoint of the chutes API to populate it.
```
curl -s https://api.chutes.ai/users/me -H "Authorization: <chutes api key>"
```
The hotkey_name is just the base filename of your hotkey, which in the example would be `your-hotkey`. That file, the full path being `~/.bittensor/wallets/your-coldkey/hotkeys/your-hotkey` contains JSON data, which includes `ss58Address` and `secretSeed`. Grab those and update the corresponding config section. The `hotkey_seed` field has one caveat which is that you should remove the `0x` prefix from the `secretSeed` value that you grab from the hotkey file.

The last step is to actually update your chutes account with the coldkey and hotkey you just created so it matches the config, via the `/users/change_bt_auth`:
https://api.chutes.ai/docs#/Users/change_bt_auth_users_change_bt_auth_post
For example:
```
curl -XPOST https://api.chutes.ai/users/change_bt_auth -H "Authorization: <fingerprint>" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"coldkey": "ss58 of the coldkey, from ~/.bittensor/wallets/your-coldkey/coldkeypub.txt", "hotkey": "ss58Address from the hotkey"}'
```

Should not have any issues doing so - devices can't switch between hotkeys multiple times in one day but the same hotkey or 1 time per day for example is fine.
Thank you. Since the devices in Data Center A are about to expire, I plan to use the same number and type of devices in Data Center B to continue running. I assume this won't affect my rating, right?

Nothing happens per se it's just that the scores for all miners are calculated as a sum of values from the current timestamp to current timestamp minus 7 days. So, if you are on day one, your total score will be much lower than other miners because your data includes only one day out of the potential 7. Every scoring interval, the time range for values is always now - 7 days. So basically, your score should be increasing steadily over the first 7 days of mining and eventually stabilize (with changes from other miners changing their inventories and compute units shifting etc.).

Outside of any downtime, there's no additional penalty. There are a couple checks, for example the "thrashing" detection where you can't deploy models if you continuously delete the instances (miner initialized, not from failure) and your mean instance lifetime for that chute is significantly less than other miners, etc; but this very, very seldomly triggered and it really only affects miners that are rotating chutes constantly so it shouldn't be a problem for a migration.
(I'm hesitant to give you a blanket statement that you will have no problems, but a simple migration of devices should be fine)

Each chute has a `version` field, and an `updated_at` timestamp. The chute can be updated in non-code ways however, i.e. the readme can be changed without modifying the code. For example if the underlying chutes SDK is updated or the inference engine is changed (e.g. sglang 0.4.5 > 0.4.6.post4), etc. If you want to lock it down entirely, you'd probably want to deploy your own chute.

```

kubectl rollout restart deployment/gepetto -n chutes
kubectl create configmap gepetto-code --from-file=gepetto.py -o yaml --dry-run=client | kubectl apply -n chutes -f -
